        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer263010288" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6090779920863747261">this book is far more even in its well-spun humor than <i>coyote v. acme</i> so i can recommend this book for a light-hearted yet jaundiced-eyed look at modern life. &quot;laws concerning food and drink; household principles; lamentations of the father&quot; is close to perfect and can be appreciated by mothers and fathers. &quot;th-th-that&apos;s not all, folks&quot; is a spoof on biography writing by way of cartoon characters and is an excellent send-up of biography writers as in herod&apos;s question &quot;what is truth?&quot; &quot;kidproof&quot; </span>
  <span id="freeText6090779920863747261" style="display:none">this book is far more even in its well-spun humor than <i>coyote v. acme</i> so i can recommend this book for a light-hearted yet jaundiced-eyed look at modern life. "laws concerning food and drink; household principles; lamentations of the father" is close to perfect and can be appreciated by mothers and fathers. "th-th-that's not all, folks" is a spoof on biography writing by way of cartoon characters and is an excellent send-up of biography writers as in herod's question "what is truth?" "kidproof" is sadly humorous and may cut too close to the bone for some mothers and absent-fathers. and "warmer, warmer" is respectfully of the quality of a jonathan swift essay/satire. and, frankly, the following two titles were down-right prescient!! "the not-so-public enemy" about osama ben laden published july-august 2011 and "come back, suckers" published may 2003 on the unethical ways-and-means of the stock market. humor as forewarning as seer career. pretty good, mr. frazier. kudos for you. while "back in the u.s.a." has an eerily dark humor to it esp. if hummers as family vehicles don't make sense to you. "if memory doesn't serve" is a perfect jewel which i want to re-read once a week just for the delight and the comfort of it! </span>
  <a data-text-id="6090779920863747261" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
